  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my kids. Growing up, my dad was a PhD in engineering, but my mom only had a high school diploma, and that gap shaped how I viewed my own potential. As a mechanic, I've seen how stereotypes about who belongs in tech can hold people back, especially women and people of color. When a girl tells me she's 'not good at math,' it's not just about math—it's about the fear that she's 'not like the others.' I've noticed this in my community, where kids who don't fit the 'typical' STEM mold get discouraged early. The solution isn't just about changing textbooks or adding more courses—it's about creating spaces where everyone feels seen and valued. For instance, when I teach my kids to fix cars, I make sure they know their skills matter, not just because they're 'good at it' but because they're *them*. Addressing stereotype threat means starting small: in my shop, I've started having conversations with young girls about how mechanics are part of science, not just 'boys' jobs. It's about dismantling the idea that STEM is a competition where only certain people win. The real change comes when we stop assuming who can or can't do something and start celebrating the diversity of how people learn and problem-solve. That's what I believe will help more kids find their voice in STEM, not just survive it.",
